 "modules": [
  {
   "title": "Module 1 · Collecting & Tabulating Data",
   "html": "<p><b>Raw data</b> is unprocessed. <b>Frequency</b> is how many times a value occurs. A <b>frequency table</b> lists the data values (or class intervals) alongside their frequencies.</p>",
   "examples": [
    {
     "q": "Given the scores 3,4,3,5,4,3,5,5, write out a frequency table.",
     "a": "Score 3: 3; Score 4: 2; Score 5: 3. Total = 8."
    }
   ]
  },
  {
   "title": "Module 2 · Bar Charts, Pie Charts, Pictograms",
   "html": "<p><b>Bar chart</b>: bars proportional to frequency, gaps between bars, categorical data.</p><p><b>Pie chart</b>: each category takes an angle proportional to its share: $\\text{angle}=\\dfrac{f}{\\Sigma f}\\times 360°$.</p><p><b>Pictogram</b>: uses a symbol to represent a fixed count of data items.</p>",
   "examples": [
    {
     "q": "In a survey of 60 students, 20 like Maths. Find the angle for Maths on a pie chart.",
     "a": "$\\tfrac{20}{60}\\times 360° = 120°$."
    }
   ]
  },
  {
   "title": "Module 3 · Histograms & Frequency Polygons",
   "html": "<p>A <b>histogram</b> shows continuous data using adjacent bars (no gaps) whose heights equal the class frequency (assuming equal class widths).</p><p>A <b>frequency polygon</b> is obtained by joining the mid-points of the tops of the histogram bars with straight lines.</p>",
   "examples": [
    {
     "q": "In a histogram, how is the frequency represented when class widths are equal?",
     "a": "By the height (or equivalently the area) of each bar."
    }
   ]
  }
 ],
